# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jet-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:jet-engine/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] A **variable cycle engine** (**VCE**), also referred to as **adaptive cycle engine** (**ACE**), is an aircraft jet engine that is designed to operate efficiently under mixed flight conditions, such as subsonic, transonic and supersonic.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] An **advanced technology engine** is a turbine engine that allows different turbines to spin at different, individually optimum speeds, instead of at one speed for all.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] It emerged on larger airplanes, before finding other applications.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The next generation of supersonic transport (SST) may require some form of VCE.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] To reduce aircraft drag at supercruise, SST engines require a high specific thrust (net thrust/airflow) to minimize the powerplant's cross-sectional area.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] This implies a high jet velocity during supersonic cruise and at take-off, which makes the aircraft noisy.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] So for zero flight velocity, specific thrust is directly proportional to jet velocity.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The Rolls-Royce/Snecma Olympus 593 in Concorde had a high specific thrust in supersonic cruise and at dry take-off.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The problem was compounded by the need for a modest amount of afterburning (reheat) at take-off (and transonic acceleration).
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] One SST VCE concept is the tandem fan engine.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The engine has two fans, both mounted on the low-pressure shaft, separated by a significant axial gap.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The engine operates in series mode while cruising and parallel mode while take-off, climb-out, approach, and final-descent.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In series mode, air enters in the front of the engine.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] After passing through the front fan, the air passes directly into the second fan, so that the engine behaves much like a turbofan.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In parallel mode, air leaving the front fan exits the engine through an auxiliary nozzle on the underside of the nacelle, skipping the rear fan.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Intakes on each side of the engine open to capture air and send it directly to the rear fan and the rest of the engine.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Parallel mode substantially increases the total air accelerated by the engine, lowering the velocity of the air and accompanying noise.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In the 1970s, Boeing modified a Pratt & Whitney JT8D to use a tandem fan configuration and successfully demonstrated the switch from series to parallel operation (and vice versa) with the engine running, albeit at partial power.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In the mid-tandem fan concept, a high specific flow single stage fan is located between the high pressure (HP) and low pressure (LP) compressors of a turbojet core.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The LP compressor exit flow passes through passages within the fan disc, directly underneath the fan blades.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Some bypass air enters the engine via an auxiliary intake.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] During take-off and approach the engine behaves much like a conventional turbofan, with an acceptable jet noise level (i.e., low specific thrust).
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] However, for supersonic cruise, the fan variable inlet guide vanes and auxiliary intake close to minimize bypass flow and increase specific thrust.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In this mode the engine acts more like a 'leaky' turbojet (e.g. the F404).
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In the mixed-flow turbofan with ejector concept, a low bypass ratio engine is mounted in front of a long tube, called an ejector.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] It is deployed during take-off and approach.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Turbofan exhaust gases send air into the ejector via an auxiliary air intake, thereby reducing the specific thrust/mean jet velocity of the final exhaust.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The mixed-flow design is not particularly efficient at low speed, but is considerably simpler.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The three-stream architecture adds a third, directable air stream.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] This stream bypasses the core when fuel efficiency is required or through the core for greater power.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Examples include the General Electric XA100 and the Pratt & Whitney XA101, as well as the propulsion system for the Next Generation Air Dominance (NGAD) fighter.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] General Electric developed a variable cycle engine, known as the GE37 or General Electric YF120, for the YF-22/YF-23 fighter aircraft competition, in the late 1980s.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] GE used a double bypass/hybrid fan arrangement, but never disclosed how they exploited the concept.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The Air Force instead selected the conventional Pratt & Whitney F119 for what became the Lockheed Martin F-22 Raptor.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Geared turbofans are also used in the following engines, some still in development: Garrett TFE731, Lycoming ALF 502/LF 507, Pratt & Whitney PW1000G, Turbomeca Astafan, and Turbomeca Aspin, and Aviadvigatel PD-18R.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The Rolls Royce Ultrafan is the largest and most efficient engine to allow multiple turbine speeds.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Startup Astro Mechanica is developing what it calls a turboelectric-adaptive jet engine that shifts from turbofan to turbojet to ramjet mode as it accelerates from a standing start to a projected Mach 6.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] This is achieved by using a dual turbine approach.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The second turbine acts as the propulsion unit.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The turbogenerator powers an electric motor that controls the compressor of the second turbine.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The motor can change speeds to keep the fan turning at the ideal RPM for a specific flight mode.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In turbojet and ramjet modes, the inlet is narrowed to compress the air and eliminate bypass.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The turbogenerator is commercially available, while the propulsion unit is built by the company.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] A key innovation is that electric motors have dramatically increased their power density so that the weight of the motor is no longer prohibitive.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Instead of a fixed gearbox, it uses an electric motor to turn the turbine(s) behind the fan at an ideal speed for each phase of flight.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The company claimed it would support efficient take-off, subsonic, supersonic, and hypersonic speeds.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The electric motor is powered by a generator in turn powered by a turbine.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The approach relies on the improved power density of novel electric motors such as yokeless dual-rotor axial flux motors that offer far more kw/kg than conventional designs that were too heavy for such an application.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Air flows in through a turbogenerator to produce electric power to power an electric motor.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The electric motor adaptively controls the propulsion unit, allowing it to behave like a turbofan, turbojet, or ramjet depending on airspeed.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In effect the engine can operate at any point along the specific impulse (Isp) curve - high Isp at low speed or low Isp at high speed.
[src:jet-engine/advanced-technology-engine] It is in some respects similar to turbo-electric marine engines that allow propellers to turn at a different speed than the steam turbines that power them.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] An **aeolipile**, **aeolipyle**, or **eolipile**, also known as a **Hero's** (or **Heron's**) **engine**, is a simple, bladeless radial steam turbine which spins when the central water container is heated.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] Torque is produced by steam jets exiting the turbine.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] The Greek-Egyptian mathematician and engineer Hero of Alexandria described the device in the 1st century CE, and many sources give him the credit for its invention.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] However, at least one source credits Vitruvius as the first to describe this appliance in his *De architectura* (c.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] The aeolipile is considered to be the first recorded steam engine or reaction steam turbine, but it is neither a practical source of power nor a direct predecessor of the type of steam engine invented during the Industrial Revolution.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] The name – derived from the Ancient Greek name Αἴολος and the Latin word *pila* – translates literally to 'the ball of Aeolus', Aeolus being the Greek god of the air and wind.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] Because it applies steam to perform work, an aeolipile (depicted in profile) is used as the symbol for the U.S.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] Navy's Boiler Technician Rate, as it was for the earlier Watertender, Boilermaker, and Boilerman ratings.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] The aeolipile usually consists of a spherical or cylindrical vessel with oppositely bent or curved nozzles projecting outwards.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] When the vessel is pressurised with steam, the gas is expelled out of the nozzles, which generates thrust due to the rocket principle as a consequence of the 2nd and 3rd of Newton's laws of motion.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] When the nozzles, pointing in different directions, produce forces along different lines of action perpendicular to the axis of the bearings, the thrusts combine to result in a rotational moment (mechanical couple), or torque, causing the vessel to spin about its axis.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] Aerodynamic drag and frictional forces in the bearings build up quickly with increasing rotational speed (rpm) and consume the accelerating torque, eventually cancelling it and achieving a steady state speed.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] Typically, and as Hero described the device, the water is heated in a simple boiler which forms part of a stand for the rotating vessel.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] Where this is the case, the boiler is connected to the rotating chamber by a pair of pipes that also serve as the pivots for the chamber.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] Alternatively the rotating chamber may itself serve as the boiler, and this arrangement greatly simplifies the pivot/bearing arrangements, as they then do not need to pass steam.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] This can be seen in the illustration of a classroom model shown here.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] Both Hero and Vitruvius draw on the much earlier work by Ctesibius (285–222 BCE), also known as Ktēsíbios or Tesibius, who was an inventor and mathematician in Alexandria, Ptolemaic Egypt.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] He wrote the first known treatises on the science of compressed air and its uses in pumps.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] It is not known whether the aeolipile was put to any practical use in ancient times, and if it was seen as a pragmatic device, a whimsical novelty, an object of reverence, or some other thing.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] A source described it as a mere curiosity for the ancient Greeks, or a "party trick".
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] Hero's drawing shows a standalone device, and was presumably intended as a "temple wonder", like many of the other devices described in *Pneumatica*.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] Vitruvius, on the other hand, mentions use of the aeolipile for demonstrating the physical properties of the weather.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] This account was preserved by the royal Spanish archives at Simancas.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] It is proposed that de Garay used Hero's aeolipile and combined it with the technology used in Roman boats and late medieval galleys.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] Here, de Garay's invention introduced an innovation where the aeolipile had practical usage, which was to generate motion to the paddlewheels, demonstrating the feasibility of steam-driven boats.
[src:jet-engine/aeolipile] This claim was denied by Spanish authorities.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The **Aero L-159 ALCA** is a subsonic light combat aircraft and advanced trainer developed in the single-seat L-159A and two-seat L-159B versions, respectively, produced in the Czech Republic by Aero Vodochody.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] It was derived from the Aero L-59 Super Albatros trainer, which was in turn developed from the Aero L-39 Albatros series.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Development of the L-159 started in 1993 as an initiative to replace various Soviet-era fighter aircraft with a modern Czech-built equivalent; it was decided against pursuing a clean-sheet design to avoid excessive costs.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Development was supported by the Czech government, which ordered 72 L-159A single-seat aircraft for roughly 50 billion CZK to equip the Czech Air Force.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] In 1998, the Boeing Company became a strategic partner in both the project and Aero Vodochody itself.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] On 4 August 1997, the L-159 performed its maiden flight; on 10 April 2000, the first production aircraft was delivered to the Czech Air Force.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Further development of the type proceeded, particularly of the twin-seat L-159 models.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] In 2003, the Czech fleet of 72 L-159A aircraft was reduced to 24 due to budget constraints.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Following several years of storage, the Czech government has re-sold most of the redundant aircraft to both military and civilian operators, namely the Iraqi Air Force and Draken International.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159 has seen active combat use by the Iraqi Air Force against Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIS) insurgents in the country.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] In Draken's service, the L-159 (colloquially known as "Honey Badger") has been employed as an aggressor aircraft for pilot training.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Since 2007, six L-159A aircraft have been rebuilt into T1 trainer derivatives.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] During 2017, Aero Vodochody formally restarted production of the type, and unveiled a newly built L-159T1 for the Iraqi Air Force; furthermore, the Czech Air Force was in the process of acquiring L-159T2 two-seaters.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Immediately after the 1989 Velvet Revolution, the president of Czechoslovakia Václav Havel declared a demobilisation of the Czechoslovak defence industry.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Nevertheless, after the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991, the Czech company Aero Vodochody continued developing the basic L-39 Albatros design with a view toward greater export.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The resulting L-39MS, later designed as L-59 Super Albatros, featured a more powerful turbofan engine, advanced avionics, and has been bought in quantity by Egypt and Tunisia.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] In 1993, a group of Czech military experts launched a project to produce a modern domestic fighter to replace the obsolete Soviet aircraft.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Since the proposed Aero L-X supersonic fighter development proved to be financially demanding (up to US$2 billion), the less costly L-159 subsonic attack aircraft, derived from the L-39 Albatros, was approved for procurement instead.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] During 1995, the Czech government placed a large order for 72 L-159A single-seat aircraft at a cost around 50 billion CZK.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The number of aircraft to be delivered was based upon the size of the Czech Air Force at that time, taking into account the necessity to replace MiG-23BN and Su-22 fighter-bombers and Su-25 attack aircraft.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Due to the cost of the project, the Czech government decided that a strategic partner, the Boeing Company, would be invited to collaborate with Aero Vodochody in the venture during May 1998.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The maiden flight of the first L-159 prototype (5831, "376 white") occurred on 2 August 1997 with a two-seat version.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] On 18 August 1998, the single-seat L-159A prototype (5832, "356 white") first flew; it was completed to Czech customer specifications.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] On 10 April 2000, the first delivery of the L-159A took place to the Czech Air Force.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Prototype (6073) of the two-seat L-159B variant first flew on 1 June 2002.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] During October 2004, the Czech government announced that Aero Vodochody was to be privatised, and Boeing decided to withdraw from involvement in both the L-159 and the overall company.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] During October 2006, Aero Vodochody was sold to Penta Investments.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] In 2009, Aero Vodochody selected *V-Dot Systems* (split off from Boeing) as the L-159 avionics integrator.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] V-Dot will replace the Honeywell multi-function displays (MFD) and upgrade the mission processors to support new functions.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] On 31 March 2017, following a 13-year stoppage in L-159 production after the delivery of the final Czech Air Force example, Aero Vodochody held a ceremony to mark the resumption of manufacturing; a new-build L-159 destined for the Iraqi Air Force was present.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] This batch of production aircraft featured several improvements, such as the use of a wet wing and increased endurance; further enhancements were also being worked on at that time.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The company reportedly negotiated with Argentina on the topic of the L-159, which reportedly may have included the establishment of an assembly line in the country.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159 ALCA is designed for the principal role of light combat aircraft (single-seat L-159A variant) or light attack jet and advanced/lead-in fighter trainer (two-seat L-159B and T variants).
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Design of the L-159 was derived from the L-39/59 in terms of aerodynamic configuration but a number of changes were made to improve its combat capabilities.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] These include strengthening of the airframe, reinforcing of the cockpit with composite and ceramic ballistic armour and enlargement of the aircraft's nose to accommodate the radar.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Compared to the L-59, the number of underwing pylons was increased from four to six, and a new hardpoint under the fuselage was added instead of a GSh-23L cannon.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The aircraft is powered by the non-afterburning Honeywell/ITEC F124-GA-100 turbofan engine with a maximum thrust of 28 kN.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Almost 2,000 litres of fuel are stored in eight internal tanks (six in the fuselage, two at the wingtips) with up to four external drop tanks (two 500 L and two 350 L tanks) carried under the wings.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The lightly armoured cockpit is equipped with a VS-2B ejection seat capable of catapulting the pilot at a zero flight level and zero speed.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The aircraft's avionics, based on the MIL-STD-1553 databus, include Selex Navigation and Attack Suite, Ring Laser Gyro based Inertial Navigation System (INS) and Global Positioning System (GPS).
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Flight data are displayed both on the FV-3000 head-up display (HUD) and two multi-function displays (MFD).
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Communications are provided by a pair of Collins ARC-182 transceivers.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Self-protection of the L-159 is ensured by the Sky Guardian 200 radar warning receiver (RWR) and the Vinten Vicon 78 Series 455 chaff and flare dispenser.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] L-159A and T2 variants are equipped with the Italian FIAR Grifo L multi-mode Doppler radar for all-weather, day and night operations.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] All variants of L-159 are equipped with a total of seven hardpoints (one under-fuselage and six under-wing mountings), capable of carrying external loads up to 2,340 kg.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The aircraft can be equipped with a variety of weapons ranging from unguided bombs and rocket pods to air-to-ground and air-to-air guided missiles or with special devices to conduct aerial reconnaissance or electronic warfare.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] For example, it is capable of carrying advanced targeting pods including the AN/AAQ-28(V) LITENING.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The Czech Air Force is the primary operator of the L-159.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] During 1995, the Czech government ordered 72 aircraft, but after review, opted to reduce the fleet size to 24 L-159s, which received the latest avionics upgrades, while the remaining aircraft were placed into long-term storage.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] By 2016, the Czech Air Force had 16 L-159A and 5 L-159T1 aircraft in service.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] On 1 June 2016, Aero Vodochody received an order to upgrade an initial batch of 16 Czech Air Force L-159s.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] On 15 October 2012, it was announced that Iraq had agreed to purchase 28 L-159s from the Czech government.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] During early 2015, Iraq signed a deal for 14 L-159 aircraft, comprising 12 L-159As and two L-159T1s, for the Iraqi Air Force.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] This sale was politically controversial in the United Kingdom, as it necessitated the lifting of a long-standing ban on the export of British radar technology to Iraq.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The first two Czech L-159s were delivered to Iraq on 5 November 2015.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] In May 2016, numerous Iraqi L-159s participated in attacks upon positions held by Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) insurgents in the city of Fallujah.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] During October and November 2016, L-159 aircraft operated by Squadron No.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] 115 were deployed in the battle against ISIL forces at the Southern outskirts of Mosul.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] As the threat posed by ISIS diminished in Iraq, the L-159s were placed into temporary storage around 2017 or 2018.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] During February 2022, it was announced that the Iraqi L159s had been brought back into active service, although they were only capable of limited operations initially.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] It had reportedly been used in multiple strikes against insurgents in ISIL hideouts in the Hamrin Mountains of Diyala province during late 2021.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] During early 2022, Iraq has been in contact with Aero Vodochody on the topic of modernising its L-159 fleet.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] As of March 2023 an Iraqi L159 was photographed carrying the Turkish Aselpod reconnaissance, surveillance and targeting pod.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] In 2009, EADS-CASA of Spain exchanged with the CzAF four CASA C-295 for three L-159As, two L-159T1s and 130 million Euros.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Later the two L-159T1s were returned by EADS-CASA to the Czech Republic as compensation for the C-295M not meeting the counter measures requirements of the CzAF at the time of delivery.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] This problem has been solved by EADS-CASA three years later and the remaining three L-159As resold by EADS-CASA to Lewis Fighter Fleet LLC.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] During 2014, it was announced that Draken International Inc., a civilian American company that cooperates with the US military for pilot training, was in the process of acquiring 21 ex-Czech Air Force L-159s.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The deal made Draken International into the world's largest private air force.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Aero Vodochody handed over the first L-159 aircraft to the company on 30 September 2015.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Draken International has secured contacts with both the United States Air Force and the Royal Air Force to use its L-159s as aggressor aircraft for pilot training.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] A separate company, Lewis Fighter Fleet LLC, also operates three L-159As for its own purposes.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] These aircraft, which were formerly owned by EADS-CASA, were acquired by the firm in July 2013.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159A ALCA is a single-seat light multi-role combat aircraft designed for a variety of air-to-air, air-to-ground and reconnaissance missions.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The aircraft is equipped with a multi-mode Doppler Grifo-L radar (a variant of the Grifo-F x-band multi-mode, pulse-doppler radar), for all-weather, day and night operations.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] It can carry a wide range of NATO standard stores including air-to-air and air-to-ground missiles and laser guided bombs.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159A is in operational service with the Czech and Iraqi air forces.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] There are two different configurations being used by the Czech Air Force – using the Honeywell 4x4 inch MFDs or the Vdot 5x6.7 inch MFDs.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Avionic upgrades are designed and developed by V-Dot Systems Inc.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159E ALCA is the export designation of L-159A in service with Draken International.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Combat-capable variant first unveiled at the Farnborough Airshow on 16 July 2018.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Developed in collaboration with Israel Aerospace Industries and powered by a Honeywell F124-GA-100 engine.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Air Force Light Attack/Armed Reconnaissance program.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159B, also known as L-159B Albatros II, is a two-seat version primarily designed for Advanced and Operational/Lead-In Fighter Training.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159B configuration can also be tailored to customer specific requirements and adapted to needs of basic training as well as combat missions including air-to-ground, patrol and reconnaissance missions.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] On 23 July 2002, the Czech military signed a letter of intent on acquisition of the first two L-159B aircraft.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] However, due to the budget constraints the trade did not materialize.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The only prototype has been rebuilt by Aero Vodochody into **L-159T2X** demonstrator.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The aircraft's designation was changed on 14 December 2015.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159T1 is a two-seat trainer derivative used by the Czech and Iraqi Air Force.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] All L-159T1s (excluding one newly built L-159T1 for the Iraqi Air Force) are modified L-159A airframes taken from storage.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Unlike L-159A, they have just one MFD in each cockpit and no radar.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] L-159T1 S/N 6069 made its first flight on 8 March 2007 and the first batch of four aircraft was handed over to the Czech Air Force on 23 November 2007.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Another two aircraft were delivered in August and December 2010, respectively.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] L-159T1 S/N 6069 was transferred to Aero Vodochody on 30 June 2015 as a part of the Iraqi contract which included handover of four actively used aircraft – three L-159A and one L-159T1 – to the Iraqi Air Force.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Prototype L-159T1+ S/N 6067 (manufactured as L-159A in 2003 and converted to L-159T1 in 2007) was unveiled by Aero Vodochody in March 2017.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] L-159T1+ aircraft are characterized by an upgraded mission system, avionics and newly installed Grifo-L radar, offering the same combat capability as the single-seat L-159A.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The T1+ modernization of 4 Czech Air Force L-159T1 is scheduled to be completed in December 2019.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159T2 is a two-seat trainer with full combat capability converted from stored L-159A airframes.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Compared to the L-159T1, it has a higher proportion of newly manufactured components and a Grifo-L radar installed.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Instead of mirroring the instruments to the rear seat, the new two-seater will have independent instruments interchangeable with the L-159A while using the same software configuration.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] The Czech Air Force has ordered 3 L-159T2 aircraft scheduled to be delivered in November 2018.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] On 11 May 2023, Czech President Petr Pavel, in a radio interview, offered the L-159 to Ukraine.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] Subject to a decision by the Czech government, President Pavel said “It is worth considering whether we could provide Ukraine with our L-159 aircraft.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] As direct combat support aircraft, (the planes) could also help Ukraine significantly in the counteroffensive”.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] They also carry an array of western weapons such as: “AIM-9 Sidewinder missiles, AIM-120 AMRAAM, AGM-65 Maverick, and GBU-12 Paveway II and GBU-16 Paveway II laser-guided bombs.” They also are a Czech aircraft, approval from other countries is not required.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] It is also an upgrade from the Aero L-39 Albatros that the Ukraine Air Force uses.
[src:jet-engine/aero-l-159-alca] On 16 January 2026, Czech president Petr Pavel has pledged to provide Ukraine with “medium combat planes which are highly effective in fighting drones”—this likely refers to the L-159 light fighter jet.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The **AIDC F-CK-1 Ching-Kuo** (Chinese: 經國號戰機; pinyin: *Jīngguó Hào Zhànjī*), commonly known as the **Indigenous Defense Fighter** (**IDF**), is a multirole combat aircraft named after Chiang Ching-kuo, the late president of the Republic of China.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The aircraft made its first flight in 1989.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] It entered service with Republic of China Air Force (Taiwan) in 1992.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] All 130 production aircraft were manufactured by 1999.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Taiwan initiated the IDF program when the United States refused to sell them F-20 Tigershark and F-16 Fighting Falcon jet fighters following diplomatic pressure from China.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Taiwan therefore decided to develop an advanced indigenous jet fighter.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The Aerospace Industrial Development Corporation (AIDC), based in Taichung, Taiwan, designed and built the IDF jet fighter.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The preliminary search for a replacement for the ROCAF's F-5s and F-104s began with the **XF-6** indigenous fighter project, later renamed *Ying Yang*, in the late 1970s.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] After the US established formal relations with People's Republic of China and ended the Sino-American Mutual Defense Treaty with Republic of China, President Chiang Ching-Kuo decided to expand the indigenous defense industry and on August 28, 1980, ordered AIDC to design an indigenous interceptor.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Originally, the ROCAF listed the priority of the XF-6 behind the XA-3 *Lei Ming* single seat attack aircraft, due to the believed high risks of the XF-6 project.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The signing of the 1982 US-China Joint Communiqué limited arms sales to Taiwan.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Although US President Ronald Reagan reluctantly accepted his advisers' suggestion of building relations with China to counter the USSR, Reagan decided to balance the 1982 US-PRC Communiqué with the "Six Assurances" to Taiwan.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] This opened the door for US technology transfer and assistance to Taiwan's defense industry, including the IDF project.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The AIDC officially began the IDF development project in May 1982 following the ROCAF's failure to purchase new fighters from the United States as a result of Chinese diplomatic pressure.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] In April 1997 American company Litton's Applied Technology division was awarded a production contract and options totaling $116.2 million by the Aerospace Industrial Development Corporation for Improved Radar Warning Receivers (IRWR) to be installed aboard.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Joint investment with Garrett became the only practical solution.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] In 1978, following the success of the TFE731 engine, U.S. engine company Garrett announced joint research of the TFE1042 afterburner with the Swedish company Volvo Flygmotor.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] After the initial negotiation, the investment was going to be divided between Garrett, Volvo, AIDC, and the Italian company Piaggio.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The development would consist of the non-afterburning TFE1042-6 for light attack aircraft and advanced trainers, and the TFE1042-7 for the AMX or the F-5 upgrade.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] AIDC also suggested upgrading the TFE1042-7 to 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust in a twin-engine installation, in order to compete with the GE F404.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] However, the JAS 39 Gripen project decided to continue with a single F404, and Piaggio asked to participate at a later date due to financial concerns.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] ITEC completely redesigned the TFE1042-7 into the TFE1042-70 – for example, the bypass ratio was changed from 0.84 to 0.4, and the investment had increased from US$180 million to about US$320 million.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] However, to avoid pressures from China, the US government had asked all American companies cooperating with the Taiwan on the IDF project to remain low-key.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Therefore, the perception that "the TFE1042 is merely the civilian engine TFE731 with an afterburner" was never completely dispelled.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] In 1985, the preliminary review of the IDF's design revealed some performance requirement shortfalls, and it was determined that an upgrade of engine thrust by 10% was the simplest solution.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Due to American export license restrictions, ITEC used FADEC to artificially limit the thrust below a certain altitude (the restriction was not removed until 1990).
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Although the upgrade essentially used the TFE1088-11 configuration, to reduce political interference ITEC renamed the original, lower-thrust version as the TFE1042-X70 and retained the TFE1042-70 designation for the upgraded version.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] In 1988, ITEC decided to invest in the 12,000 lbf (53 kN) thrust TFE1088-12, which was re-designated as the TFE1042-70A for political reason as well.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Preliminary studies had shown that the IDF could supercruise with the new engine.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] At the same time, General Electric Aviation decided to enter the market with the J101/SF, a smaller version of the F404.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] However, after the IDF order was cut in half due to budget concerns, the TFE1088-12 engine upgrade plan ended as well.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] GD's assistance was restricted by the US State Department's arms export control, which limited GD's work to initial design consulting but not further development, production, or marketing.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Many different airframe design concepts were explored (e.g. the 2D Thrust-Vectoring nozzle of XX-201, the double delta wings/twin tailed 401).
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] After the General Electric J79 was officially abandoned as the potential engine solution in 1983, three configurations emerged from AIDC.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] At the same time, GD worked on the G configuration in parallel.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Eventually the G-4 was selected, but with many features of the C-2 integrated.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] During this time, the project was named the "Light Weight Defense Fighter".
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] In 1985, the configuration conceptual design had evolved into the SE-1 preliminary design.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] By the end of 1985, AIDC decided to skip the prototype stage and go into Full Scale Development (FSD) directly, in order to reduce time and save money.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The project was again renamed into the "Indigenous Defense Fighter".
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Four FSD aircraft were made, with three single-seaters and one double-seater.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The radar can simultaneously track 10 targets and engage two of the 10 targets tracked with TC-2 active radar seeker BVRAAMs.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The design is inherently unstable in pitch, so the IDF incorporated a modern triple-redundant full authority fly-by-wire control system.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The avionics suite was based on modular architecture with dual redundant MIL-STD-1553B digital databuses.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The Honeywell H423 inertial navigation system, the TWS-95 RHAWS, and a Bendix-King head-up display were selected.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Some capabilities may have been delayed or dropped in order to meet the performance requirement, since the engine limitation has resulted in the necessity of strict weight control.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The CSIST's *Tien Chien* (Sky Sword) project was slightly more independent, since it was considered to be a development for all the ROCAF's aircraft rather than only the IDF.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The Tien Chien 1 (TC-1) is a short range infrared-seeking missile with an external configuration similar to that of the AIM-9 Sidewinder, while the Tien Chien 2 (TC-2) is an active radar homing Beyond Visual Range missile.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The first test firing of the TC-1 missile was performed by an F-5E in April 1986, with the Beech target drone successfully destroyed.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Initial production of the TC-1 began in 1989, and it entered service in 1991.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Both the AIM-9 and the TC-1 have been seen in use on operational IDFs.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] CSIST is believed to have cooperated with Motorola and Raytheon on the TC-2's active seeker, which is believed to be based on their seeker design which was proposed for the AIM-120.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] 40 pre-production TC-2 missiles were produced before 1995, and were the only BVR AAMs that the ROCAF had in its inventory during the 1995–96 Taiwan Strait Missile Crisis.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Over 200 production TC-2s were originally planned.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] During the F-CK-1's development, it was tapped as the secondary delivery vehicle for the Taiwanese nuclear weapons then in development.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The primary delivery method was to be the Sky Horse missile.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Weapons designers at CSIST were instructed to design the nuclear weapon to fit within the dimensions of the F-CK-1's centerline drop tank (~50 cm diameter).
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Modifications to the aircraft would have been required for it to obtain the desired 1,000 km range (especially without the centerline drop tank available) and were envisioned to include more efficient non-afterburning engines.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The F-CK-1 would not have been able to fulfill the nuclear strike mission until mid-1989 at the very earliest.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Early designs called for an unpowered gravity bomb.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The nuclear weapons program was shut down under US pressure before the F-CK-1 entered service and the dedicated nuclear strike variant was never produced.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The first stage of upgrades to the fleet was originally planned to be completed by 2013, and was planned to include improved avionics, radar, electronics, weapons capabilities and lifespan extensions.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] In May 2014, the ROC Air Force made photos of the fighters with enhanced Wan Chien long-range missile capabilities public.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The upgrade program was finally completed in 2018.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Four "Full Scale Development" units were produced; three single-seaters followed by a two-seater.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The first successful test flight by single-seater FSD A1 was made on May 28, 1989.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The two-seater FSD B1 conducted its first flight on July 10, 1990.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Production of ten pre-production units began in October 1990.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The first four were delivered in March 1992 and the last in 1993.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Mechanical defects caused two crashes, one in 1991 and one in 1993, during pre-production.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The ROCAF's initial order for 256 aircraft was cut to 130 in 1991, following deals for the purchase of 150 F-16 Block 20 A/B and 60 Mirage 2000-5Ei/Di with the US and France.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The 130 included 28 two-seaters and the 10 pre-production units.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The first production units were delivered in early 1994, and the program concluded in 2000.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The first squadron entered service during the latter part of the 1994.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] Mid-life updates to the aircraft were initiated in 2011.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The Ministry of National Defense (MND) announced that beginning in 2001, the government would include a new budget allocation for the IDF upgrade plan (as included in the five MND proposals to help AIDC).
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] In 2001, it was reported that development of a new "stealth" variant with more powerful engines and improved fire-control system would commence that year.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] In a 2006 interview with *Jane's Defence Weekly*, former AIDC Chairman Sun Tao-Yu said that two new prototypes had been manufactured.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The upgrade would allow the IDF to carry an additional 771 kg of fuel.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] In addition, it includes an improved avionics suite, retrofitted electronic warfare capabilities, and new weapons systems.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The landing gear has been strengthened to accommodate the additional payload and fuel, but the plan for a dielectric radar-absorbing "stealth" fuselage was dropped due to concerns over weight.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The development contract for the upgraded 32-bit IDF C/D flight control computer was awarded in 2002 to BAE Systems.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] AIDC said that the improvements of the flight computer will result in "a safer, higher-performing aircraft.” Other improvements made include enhanced electronic warfare capabilities, a strengthened landing gear and a digital anti-skid system.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The upgrade also included new indigenous flight control software ending the reliance on US controlled source code.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The first test flight of the upgraded IDF was reportedly successfully completed a few days ahead of schedule in early October.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] On March 27, 2007, President Chen Shui-Bian witnessed a test flight of F-CK-1D, and announced that the upgraded IDF will be named *Hsiung Ying* (Brave Hawk), which signifies that the new fighter would protect the homeland just like the Crested Goshawk.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] As of 12/2009, 71 F-CK-1 A/B are upgrading to F-CK-1 C/D over 4 years span for over US$500 million, according to AIDC CEO, under Project *Hsiang Chan* (翔展), as AIDC and ROCAF had signed a contract for the expected upgrade program.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] In 2018 AIDC delivered the last upgraded F-CK-1 C/D to the Republic of China Air Force.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] According to the media, the AIDC IDF trainer concept apparently involved the removal of the fire control radar and combat systems with the retention of rear-seat flight controls, so that the IDF could be used as a lead-in fighter trainer (LIFT).
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The ROCAF seemed to have reservations with the concept, however, as it would mean the IDF LIFT would not be usable in wartime.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] A MND letter said, "Regarding the newspaper report of AIDC's desire to use the IDF fighter as a basis for supersonic trainer development, it is only that company's operational planning concept.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The Ministry of National Defense and the Air Force currently do not have such a plan".
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The letter then said that due to a tight budget allocation the ROCAF would instead ask AIDC to extend the life of the AT-3 and continue to use the F-5 in the LIFT role.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] In 2003, the former AIDC Chairman Huang Jung-Te said that AIDC still hoped the ROCAF would consider using a simplified version of the IDF for LIFT, and that such a concept could have a cost as low as US$16 million per unit, compared to the T-50's 19 million.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] However, the F-CK-1 LIFT modifications or new production concepts never received government funding or approval.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] General Cheng Shih-Yu testified that the MND indeed plans to retire the F-5E/F by 2010 and allow the in-service IDFs to take over training missions.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] It is unclear what modifications (if any) will be made to IDFs after they become trainers.
[src:jet-engine/aidc-f-ck-1-ching-kuo] The trainers produced by the program would later named AIDC T-5 Brave Eagle, and four prototypes were rolled out in 2019.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The **AMX International AMX** is a ground-attack aircraft jointly developed by Brazil and Italy.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The AMX is designated **A-11 Ghibli** by the Italian Air Force and **A-1** by the Brazilian Air Force.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The Italian name, "Ghibli", is taken from the hot dry wind of the Libyan Desert.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] During the early 1970s, Italian manufacturer Aermacchi conducted a design study on a prospective light ground-attack aircraft, which was given the designation of *MB-340*.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] In 1977, the Italian Air Force issued a requirement for 187 new-build strike fighters, which were to replace its existing Aeritalia G.91 in the close air support role.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] In 1978, both Aeritalia and Aermacchi joined to engage on a single aircraft.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] During October of the same year the Rolls Royce “Spey” was chosen by the Aeronautica Militare and the two companies started the real development of the AMX that was widely based on the Aeritalia Model 3-20 project.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] In 1980, the Brazilian government announced that they intended to participate in the program in order to provide a replacement for the Aermacchi MB-326 used by the Brazilian Air Force.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] As a result of a memorandum between Italy and Brazil for the aircraft's joint development in 1981, AMX International, an Italian-Brazilian joint venture, was formed to develop, manufacture, and market the aircraft.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] During early 1977, the Italian Air Force issued a requirement for 187 new-build strike fighters, which were to replace its existing Aeritalia G.91 in the close air support and reconnaissance missions, as well as the Lockheed RF-104G Starfighter also being used in the reconnaissance role.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Rather than competing for the contract, Aeritalia (now Alenia Aeronautica) and Aermacchi agreed to produce a joint proposal for the requirement, as both firms had been considering the development of a similar class of aircraft for some years.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] During the early 1970s, Aermacchi conducted work on a design study for such a light ground attack aircraft under the designation of *MB-340*.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] In April 1978, development work on the joint venture formally commenced.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] During October of the same year the Rolls Royce “Spey” was chosen by the Aeronautica Militare and the two companies started the real development of the AMX that was widely based on the early 1970s Aeritalia Model 3-20 project.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] During 1980, the Brazilian government announced that they intended to participate in the program in order to provide a replacement for the Aermacchi MB-326.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] In July 1981, the Italian and Brazilian governments agreed on joint requirements for the aircraft, and Embraer was invited to join the industrial partnership.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] There was no duplication of work, each component of the aircraft was built at one source only.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The planned requirements were 187 aircraft for Italy and 100 for Brazil.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Final deliveries were 136 aircraft for the Italian Air Force (110 AMX & 26 AMX-T) and 94 airplanes for the Brazilian Air Force (79 AMX & 15 AMX-T) for a total of 230 planes between the two countries.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] In the early stages of development, various different powerplants and engine configurations were studied to power the type; both twin-engine and single-engine approaches were considered.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The use of US-sourced engines had been promptly discounted to avoid any potential restrictions on export sales of the overall aircraft.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Amongst the engines examined were the Turbo-Union RB199 (as used by the larger Panavia Tornado), the Rolls-Royce Turbomeca Adour, Rolls-Royce Viper, and the Rolls-Royce Spey engine.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] In 1978, the Spey 807 model, which featured several additional improvements, was selected to power the new aircraft.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Key features that were reportedly emphasised in the design process of the new aircraft were accessibility and survivability; the AMX had to be able to sustain a single failure to any onboard system without any performance degradation.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] To achieve this, key systems are duplicated and vital systems are protected; the use of cockpit armor was considered but ultimately discounted due to the expense involved.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The detailed definition phase of the project was completed in March 1980.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] A total of seven flight-capable prototypes were produced for the test program, three by Aeritalia, two by Aermacchi, and two by Embraer, as well as two static airframes.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The first prototype, assembled in Italy, made its maiden flight on 15 May 1984.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] This first aircraft was lost on its fifth flight in an accident, resulting in the death of its pilot.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Aside from this early loss, testing progressed without further incident.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The first Brazilian-assembled prototype made its first flight on 16 October 1985.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] On 11 May 1988, the first production aircraft performed its first flight.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Deliveries of production aircraft to Italy began in 1988, the first units were delivered to the Brazilian Air Force during the following year.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] On 14 March 1990, the prototype two-seat AMX made its first flight.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The AMX is a conventional shoulder-winged monoplane.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] It is composed primarily of aluminium and manufactured using traditional construction methods, however elements such as the tail fin and elevators use carbon fibre composite materials.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] For its size, a large proportion of the AMX's internal space is allocated to avionics and onboard computer systems.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Both the navigation and attack systems are computerized.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] For accessibility and ease of maintenance, all avionics are installed directly in bays beneath the cockpit in a manner in which they can be worked upon at ground level without the use of support platforms.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Manual reversion is provided for the ailerons, elevator and rudder to allow the aircraft to be flown even in the event of complete hydraulic failure; either control system can act independent of the other.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The wing is fitted with both leading edge slats and trailing edge flaps and overwing spoilers ahead of the flaps.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The spoilers can function as airbrakes and to negate lift; improving take-off and landing performance as well as manoeuvrability during flight.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] A single Rolls-Royce Spey turbofan engine serves as the AMX's powerplant.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] During the aircraft's development, the Spey was heavier and less modern than some of the available alternatives, but it was considered to be reliable, relatively cheap and was free of export restrictions that would be imposed by using American engines.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The Spey engine also enabled for the use of a simplified round-lipped inlet design.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The rear fuselage is detachable in order to gain access to the engine.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Separate consortia in both Brazil and Italy manufactured the Spey for the AMX.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Unusual for a strike aircraft of the era, no attempt was made to develop the aircraft to fly at supersonic speeds.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Brazilian and Italian aircraft differ considerably in their avionics, Italian aircraft being equipped with various NATO systems which were considered redundant in the South American theatre.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] AMXs in Brazilian service are often fitted with one of three pallet-mounted sensor packages, which contain various vertical, oblique, and forward-facing cameras, for performing the aircraft's secondary aerial reconnaissance role.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] A simple ranging radar is equipped for targeting purposes; however, the specific radar also differs between the two operators.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The flight system employs a GE Avionics flight control computer.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Extensive electronic countermeasures (ECM) are fitted to protect the aircraft, including passive receiver antenna on the tailfin and an active jammer pod that is typically mounted on one of the aircraft's hardpoints.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Various munitions could be mounted on the one centerline and four under-wing hardpoints, including bombs, missiles and rockets; payloads of up to 900 kg (2,000 lb) may be carried upon the centerline and the two innermost under-wing pylons, while the outer pylons can carry up to 500 kg (1,000 lb).
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] All four of the under-wing hardpoints are plumbed for drop tanks to extend the aircraft's range, Italian aircraft are also fitted with a fixed aerial refueling probe.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Optical reconnaissance pods can be carried externally on the centerline hardpoint.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Wingtip rails are provided for infrared guided air-to-air missiles such as the AIM-9 Sidewinder and MAA-1 Piranha.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Italian aircraft are fitted with an M61 Vulcan 20 mm rotary cannon on the port side of the lower fuselage.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The United States denied the sale of the M61 to Brazil, thus its AMXs are instead fitted with two 30 mm DEFA 554 revolver cannons.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The first operational squadron of the Italian air force, the 103° *Gruppo* of 51° *Stormo* formed in November 1989, with the first Italian unit also forming in 1989.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Both the Italian and Brazilian AMX fleets were grounded in February 1992, following the crash of an Italian AMX due to engine failure.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Operations were allowed to restart in May of that year, following modification of the engines.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Italy assigned six AMXs from 103° *Gruppo* to operations over Bosnia in 1995 as part of Operation Deny Flight, which was followed by a similar deployment in support of the IFOR peacekeepers in Bosnia.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] This deployment was interrupted by another grounding, again due to engine failure, between January and March 1996.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Italian AMX aircraft were used in 1999 in the Kosovo war.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Instead of using unguided or more traditional laser-guided bombs, the Italian Air Force used dozens of Mk 82 bombs fitted with Opher Israeli guidance kits, effectively converting the "dumb" bombs into an infrared-guided bomb.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] In the late 1990s, AMX International was considering a major engine refit; a non-afterburning variant of the Eurojet EJ200 was proposed, with considerably more thrust than the existing powerplant.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] In August 2007, Embraer began a major midlife upgrade programme and modernisation of 53 Brazilian Air Force AMX A-1s, focusing on avionics systems and new armament additions; the programme is estimated to have extended the lifespan of the fleet beyond 2027.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Starting in November 2009, four Italian AMXs were deployed overseas for operations in Afghanistan, replacing the same number of Italian Tornado IDS in the reconnaissance role.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Of particular note is the aircraft's ability to share digital electro-optical and infrared sensor information with ground troops in real time, providing valuable reconnaissance information and helping to minimise threat exposure.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] By the end of 2010 over 700 combat missions had been flown in the Afghan theatre.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] On 28 May 2014, the AMX performed its last combat sortie in the Afghan theatre, and on 20 June 2014, all remaining AMXs were withdrawn from Afghanistan.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] In 2011, Italian AMX aircraft were employed during the 2011 military intervention in Libya.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Italian military aircraft deployed 710 guided bombs and missiles during sorties: Italian Air Force Tornados and AMX fighter bombers deployed 550 bombs and missiles, while Navy AV-8Bs deployed 160 guided bombs.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The conflict saw the first use by AMX aircraft of Litening targeting pods paired with Paveway and JDAM guided bombs.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] In early 2016, due to the declining stability of Libya, Italy opted to station additional aircraft, including four AMX fighters, at Bassi Airbase, Trapani, Sicily.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] In March 2012, the Philippines were reportedly holding negotiations with Italy for the possible procurement of used AMX aircraft; however, on 28 March 2014, the Philippines' Department of National Defense signed a contract for 12 FA-50 light attack aircraft worth P18.9 billion (US$421.12 million).
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The Italian Air Force held a retirement ceremony on 5 April 2024 at Istrana Air Base in northern Italy.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] In 1986, development of a two-seat advanced trainer variant was undertaken.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] This was intended to provide trainee pilots with experience on fast jets, while still retaining the single-seater's attack capabilities.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] First flying in 1990, the AMX-T equipped both the Italian and Brazilian air forces.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The AMX Advanced Trainer Attack (AMX-ATA) is a new AMX two-seater multi-mission attack fighter developed for combat roles and advanced training.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The AMX-ATA incorporates new sensors, a forward-looking infrared helmet-mounted display, a new multi-mode radar for air-to-air and air-to-surface capability, and new weapons systems including anti-ship missiles and medium-range missiles.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The Venezuelan Air Force ordered eight AMX-ATA in 1999 for the advanced trainer and attack aircraft role, but the US Congress vetoed the sale because the aircraft systems include US technology.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] An AMX variant designed for reconnaissance missions.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Various reconnaissance pallets can be fitted; used by the Brazilian Air Force.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] The product of a Brazilian upgrade program of their A-1s; significant features include a Mectron SCP-01 Scipio radar, Embraer BR2 data link, FLIR Systems navigation equipment, Elbit INS/GPS/databus, the adoption of a glass cockpit, a new OBOGS system and HMD DASH IV.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Italian military designation for the AMX from 2012.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Italian military designation for the AMX-T from 2012.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Italian military designation for the AMX ACOL from 2012.
[src:jet-engine/amx-international-amx] Italian military designation for the AMX-T ACOL from 2012.
[src:jet-engine/atrex] The **ATREX** engine (**Air Turbo Ramjet Engine with eXpander cycle**) developed in Japan is an experimental precooled jet engine that works as a turbojet at low speeds and a ramjet up to mach 6.0.
[src:jet-engine/atrex] ATREX uses liquid hydrogen fuel in a fairly exotic single-fan arrangement.
[src:jet-engine/atrex] The liquid hydrogen fuel is pumped through a heat exchanger in the air-intake, simultaneously heating the liquid hydrogen and cooling the incoming air.
[src:jet-engine/atrex] This cooling of the incoming air is critical in achieving a reasonable efficiency.
[src:jet-engine/atrex] The hydrogen then continues through a second heat exchanger positioned after the combustion section, where the hot exhaust is used to further heat the hydrogen, turning it in a very high pressure gas.
[src:jet-engine/atrex] This gas is then passed through the tips of the fan providing driving power to the fan at subsonic speeds.
[src:jet-engine/atrex] After mixing with the air, the hydrogen is burned in the combustion chamber.
[src:jet-engine/atrex] The development of this engine lost focus in favor of the new hypersonic precooled turbojet engine (PCTJ).
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] A **jet engine** is a type of reaction engine, discharging a fast-moving jet of heated gas (usually air) that generates thrust by jet propulsion.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] While this broad definition may include rocket, water jet, and hybrid propulsion, the term *jet engine* typically refers to an internal combustion air-breathing jet engine such as a turbojet, turbofan, ramjet, pulse jet, or scramjet.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] In general, jet engines are internal combustion engines.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Air-breathing jet engines typically feature a rotating air compressor powered by a turbine, with the leftover power providing thrust through the propelling nozzle—this process is known as the Brayton thermodynamic cycle.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Jet aircraft use such engines for long-distance travel.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Early jet aircraft used turbojet engines that were relatively inefficient for subsonic flight.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Most modern subsonic jet aircraft use more complex high-bypass turbofan engines.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] They give higher speed and greater fuel efficiency than piston and propeller aeroengines over long distances.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] A few air-breathing engines made for high-speed applications (ramjets and scramjets) use the ram effect of the vehicle's speed instead of a mechanical compressor.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] This, combined with greatly decreased fuel consumption, permitted routine transatlantic flight by twin-engined airliners by the turn of the century, where previously a similar journey would have required multiple fuel stops.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Before the start of World War II, engineers were beginning to realize that engines driving propellers were approaching limits due to issues related to propeller efficiency, which declined as blade tips approached the speed of sound.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] If aircraft performance were to increase beyond such a barrier, a different propulsion mechanism was necessary.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] This was the motivation behind the development of the gas turbine engine, the most common form of jet engine.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The key to a practical jet engine was the gas turbine, extracting power from the engine itself to drive the compressor.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The gas turbine was not a new idea: the patent for a stationary turbine was granted to John Barber in England in 1791.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The first gas turbine to successfully run self-sustaining was built in 1903 by Norwegian engineer Ægidius Elling.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Such engines did not reach manufacture due to issues of safety, reliability, weight and, especially, sustained operation.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The first patent for using a gas turbine to power an aircraft was filed in 1921 by Maxime Guillaume.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] His engine was an axial-flow turbojet, but was never constructed, as it would have required considerable advances over the state of the art in compressors.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Alan Arnold Griffith published *An Aerodynamic Theory of Turbine Design* in 1926 leading to experimental work at the RAE.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] In 1928, RAF College Cranwell cadet Frank Whittle formally submitted his ideas for a turbojet to his superiors.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] In October 1929, he developed his ideas further.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] On 16 January 1930, in England, Whittle submitted his first patent (granted in 1932).
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The patent showed a two-stage axial compressor feeding a single-sided centrifugal compressor.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Practical axial compressors were made possible by ideas from A.A.Griffith in a seminal paper in 1926 ("An Aerodynamic Theory of Turbine Design").
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Whittle would later concentrate on the simpler centrifugal compressor only.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Whittle was unable to interest the government in his invention, and development continued at a slow pace.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] In Spain, pilot and engineer Virgilio Leret Ruiz was granted a patent for a jet engine design in March 1935.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Republican president Manuel Azaña arranged for initial construction at the Hispano-Suiza aircraft factory in Madrid in 1936, but Leret was executed months later by Francoist Moroccan troops after unsuccessfully defending his seaplane base on the first days of the Spanish Civil War.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] His plans, hidden from Francoists, were secretly given to the British embassy in Madrid a few years later by his wife, Carlota O'Neill, upon her release from prison.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] In 1935, Hans von Ohain started work on a similar design to Whittle's in Germany, both compressor and turbine being radial, on opposite sides of the same disc, initially unaware of Whittle's work.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Von Ohain's first device was strictly experimental and could run only under external power, but he was able to demonstrate the basic concept.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Ohain was then introduced to Ernst Heinkel, one of the larger aircraft industrialists of the day, who immediately saw the promise of the design.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Heinkel had recently purchased the Hirth engine company, and Ohain and his master machinist Max Hahn were set up there as a new division of the Hirth company.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] They had their first HeS 1 centrifugal engine running by September 1937.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Unlike Whittle's design, Ohain used hydrogen as fuel, supplied under external pressure.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Their subsequent designs culminated in the gasoline-fuelled HeS 3 of 5 kN (1,100 lbf), which was fitted to Heinkel's simple and compact He 178 airframe and flown by Erich Warsitz in the early morning of August 27, 1939, from Rostock-Marienehe aerodrome, an impressively short time for development.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The He 178 was the world's first jet plane.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Heinkel applied for a US patent covering the Aircraft Power Plant by Hans Joachim Pabst von Ohain on May 31, 1939; patent number US2256198, with M Hahn referenced as inventor.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Von Ohain's design, an axial-flow engine, as opposed to Whittle's centrifugal flow engine, was eventually adopted by most manufacturers by the 1950s.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Austrian Anselm Franz of Junkers' engine division (*Junkers Motoren* or "Jumo") introduced the axial-flow compressor in their jet engine.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Jumo was assigned the next engine number in the RLM 109-0xx numbering sequence for gas turbine aircraft powerplants, "004", and the result was the Jumo 004 engine.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] After many lesser technical difficulties were solved, mass production of this engine started in 1944 as a powerplant for the world's first jet-fighter aircraft, the Messerschmitt Me 262 (and later the world's first jet-bomber aircraft, the Arado Ar 234).
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] A variety of reasons conspired to delay the engine's availability, causing the fighter to arrive too late to improve Germany's position in World War II, however this was the first jet engine to be used in service.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Meanwhile, in Britain the Gloster E28/39 had its maiden flight on 15 May 1941 and the Gloster Meteor finally entered service with the RAF in July 1944.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] These were powered by turbojet engines from Power Jets Ltd., set up by Frank Whittle.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The first two operational turbojet aircraft, the Messerschmitt Me 262 and then the Gloster Meteor entered service within three months of each other in 1944; the Me 262 in April and the Gloster Meteor in July.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The Meteor only saw around 15 aircraft enter World War II action, while up to 1400 Me 262 were produced, with 300 entering combat, delivering the first ground attacks and air combat victories of jet planes.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Following the end of the war the German jet aircraft and jet engines were extensively studied by the victorious allies and contributed to work on early Soviet and US jet fighters.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The legacy of the axial-flow engine is seen in the fact that practically all jet engines on fixed-wing aircraft have had some inspiration from this design.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] By the 1950s, the jet engine was almost universal in combat aircraft, with the exception of cargo, liaison and other specialty types.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] By this point, some of the British designs were already cleared for civilian use, and had appeared on early models like the de Havilland Comet and Avro Canada Jetliner.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] By the 1960s, all large civilian aircraft were also jet powered, leaving the piston engine in low-cost niche roles such as cargo flights.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Jet engines power jet aircraft, cruise missiles and unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] In the form of rocket engines they power model rocketry, spaceflight, and military missiles.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Jet engines have propelled high speed cars, particularly drag racers, with the all-time record held by a rocket car.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] A turbofan powered car, ThrustSSC, currently holds the land speed record.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Jet engine designs are frequently modified for non-aircraft applications, as industrial gas turbines or marine powerplants.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] These are used in electrical power generation, for powering water, natural gas, or oil pumps, and providing propulsion for ships and locomotives.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Industrial gas turbines can create up to 50,000 shaft horsepower.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Many of these engines are derived from older military turbojets such as the Pratt & Whitney J57 and J75 models.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] There is also a derivative of the P&W JT8D low-bypass turbofan that creates up to 35,000 horsepower (HP).
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Jet engines are also sometimes developed into, or share certain components such as engine cores, with other gas turbine engine types.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Turboshaft and turboprop engines, which are forms of gas turbine engines that are typically used to power helicopters and some propeller-driven aircraft.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] There are a large number of different types of jet engines, all of which achieve forward thrust from the principle of *jet propulsion*.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Commonly aircraft are propelled by airbreathing jet engines.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Most airbreathing jet engines that are in use are turbofan jet engines, which give good efficiency at speeds just below the speed of sound.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] A turbojet engine is a gas turbine engine that works by compressing air with an inlet and a compressor (axial, centrifugal, or both), mixing fuel with the compressed air, burning the mixture in the combustor, and then passing the hot, high pressure air through a turbine and a nozzle.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The compressor is powered by the turbine, which extracts energy from the expanding gas passing through it.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The engine converts internal energy in the fuel to increased momentum of the gas flowing through the engine, producing thrust.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] All the air entering the compressor is passed through the combustor, and turbine, unlike the turbofan engine described below.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Turbofans differ from turbojets in that they have an additional fan at the front of the engine, which accelerates air in a duct bypassing the core gas turbine engine.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Turbofans are the dominant engine type for medium and long-range airliners.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Turbofans are usually more efficient than turbojets at subsonic speeds, but at high speeds their large frontal area generates more drag.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Therefore, in supersonic flight, and in military and other aircraft where other considerations have a higher priority than fuel efficiency, fans tend to be smaller or absent.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Because of these distinctions, turbofan engine designs are often categorized as low-bypass or high-bypass, depending upon the amount of air which bypasses the core of the engine.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Low-bypass turbofans have a bypass ratio of around 2:1 or less.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] A propfan engine is a type of airbreathing jet engine which combines aspects of turboprop and turbofan.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Its design consists of a central gas turbine which drives open-air contra-rotating propellers.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Unlike turboprop engines, in which the propeller and the engine are considered two separate products, the propfan’s gas generator and its unshrouded propeller module are heavily integrated and are considered to be a single product.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Additionally, the propfan’s short, heavily twisted variable pitch blades closely remember the ducted fan blades of turbofan engines.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Propfans are designed to offer the speed and performance of turbofan engines with fuel efficiency of turboprops.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] However, due to low fuel costs and high cabin noise, early propfan projects were abandoned.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Very few aircraft have flown with propfans, with the Antonov An-70 being the first and only aircraft to fly while being powered solely by propfan engines.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The term Advanced technology engine refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The principle is that a turbine engine will function more efficiently if the various sets of turbines can revolve at their individual optimum speeds, instead of at the same speed.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The true advanced technology engine has a triple spool, meaning that instead of having a single drive shaft, there are three, in order that the three sets of blades may revolve at different speeds.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] An interim state is a twin-spool engine, allowing only two different speeds for the turbines.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Ram compression jet engines are airbreathing engines similar to gas turbine engines in so far as they both use the Brayton cycle.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Gas turbine and ram compression engines differ, however, in how they compress the incoming airflow.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Whereas gas turbine engines use axial or centrifugal compressors to compress incoming air, ram engines rely only on air compressed in the inlet or diffuser.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] A ram engine thus requires a substantial initial forward airspeed before it can function.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Ramjets are considered the simplest type of air breathing jet engine because they have no moving parts in the engine proper, only in the accessories.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Scramjets differ mainly in the fact that the air does not slow to subsonic speeds.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] They are efficient at even higher speed.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The rocket engine uses the same basic physical principles of thrust as a form of reaction engine, but is distinct from the jet engine in that it does not require atmospheric air to provide oxygen; the rocket carries all components of the reaction mass.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] However some definitions treat it as a form of jet propulsion.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Because rockets do not breathe air, this allows them to operate at arbitrary altitudes and in space.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] This type of engine is used for launching satellites, space exploration and crewed access, and permitted landing on the Moon in 1969.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Rocket engines are used for high altitude flights, or anywhere where very high accelerations are needed since rocket engines themselves have a very high thrust-to-weight ratio.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] However, the high exhaust speed and the heavier, oxidizer-rich propellant results in far more propellant use than turbofans.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Even so, at extremely high speeds they become energy-efficient.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Where $F_{N}$ is the net thrust, $I_{\text{sp,vac}}$ is the specific impulse, $g_{0}$ is a standard gravity, ${\dot {m}}$ is the propellant flow in kg/s, $A_{e}$ is the cross-sectional area at the exit of the exhaust nozzle, and p is the atmospheric pressure.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] Combined-cycle engines simultaneously use two or more different principles of jet propulsion.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] A water jet, or pump-jet, is a marine propulsion system that uses a jet of water.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The mechanical arrangement may be a ducted propeller with nozzle, or a centrifugal compressor and nozzle.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p01] The pump-jet must be driven by a separate engine such as a Diesel or gas turbine.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] All jet engines are reaction engines that generate thrust by emitting a jet of fluid rearwards at relatively high speed.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The forces on the inside of the engine needed to create this jet give a strong thrust on the engine which pushes the craft forwards.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Jet engines make their jet from propellant stored in tanks that are attached to the engine (as in a 'rocket') as well as in **duct engines** (those commonly used on aircraft) by ingesting an external fluid (very typically air) and expelling it at higher speed.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] A propelling nozzle produces a high velocity exhaust jet.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Propelling nozzles turn internal and pressure energy into high velocity kinetic energy.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The total pressure and temperature don't change through the nozzle but their static values drop as the gas speeds up.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The velocity of the air entering the nozzle is low, about Mach 0.4, a prerequisite for minimizing pressure losses in the duct leading to the nozzle.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The temperature entering the nozzle may be as low as sea level ambient for a fan nozzle in the cold air at cruise altitudes.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] It may be as high as the 1000 Kelvin exhaust gas temperature for a supersonic afterburning engine or 2200 K with afterburner lit.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The pressure entering the nozzle may vary from 1.5 times the pressure outside the nozzle, for a single stage fan, to 30 times for the fastest manned aircraft at Mach 3+.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Convergent nozzles are only able to accelerate the gas up to local sonic (Mach 1) conditions.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] To reach high flight speeds, even greater exhaust velocities are required, and so a convergent-divergent nozzle is needed on high-speed aircraft.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The engine thrust is highest if the static pressure of the gas reaches the ambient value as it leaves the nozzle.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] This only happens if the nozzle exit area is the correct value for the nozzle pressure ratio (npr).
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Since the npr changes with engine thrust setting and flight speed this is seldom the case.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Also at supersonic speeds the divergent area is less than required to give complete internal expansion to ambient pressure as a trade-off with external body drag.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Other underexpanded examples were the XB-70 and SR-71.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The nozzle size, together with the area of the turbine nozzles, determines the operating pressure of the compressor.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] A jet engine at rest, as on a test stand, sucks in fuel and generates thrust.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] How well it does this is judged by how much fuel it uses and what force is required to restrain it.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] If something deteriorates inside the engine (known as performance deterioration) it will be less efficient and this will show when the fuel produces less thrust.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] If a change is made to an internal part which allows the air/combustion gases to flow more smoothly the engine will be more efficient and use less fuel.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] A standard definition is used to assess how different things change engine efficiency and also to allow comparisons to be made between different engines.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] This definition is called specific fuel consumption, or how much fuel is needed to produce one unit of thrust.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] For example, it will be known for a particular engine design that if some bumps in a bypass duct are smoothed out the air will flow more smoothly giving a pressure loss reduction of x% and y% less fuel will be needed to get the take-off thrust, for example.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] This understanding comes under the engineering discipline Jet engine performance.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] How efficiency is affected by forward speed and by supplying energy to aircraft systems is mentioned later.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The efficiency of the engine is controlled primarily by the operating conditions inside the engine which are the pressure produced by the compressor and the temperature of the combustion gases at the first set of rotating turbine blades.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The pressure is the highest air pressure in the engine.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The turbine rotor temperature is not the highest in the engine but is the highest at which energy transfer takes place (higher temperatures occur in the combustor).
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The above pressure and temperature are shown on a Thermodynamic cycle diagram.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The efficiency is further modified by how smoothly the air and the combustion gases flow through the engine, how well the flow is aligned (known as incidence angle) with the moving and stationary passages in the compressors and turbines.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Non-optimum angles, as well as non-optimum passage and blade shapes can cause thickening and separation of Boundary layers and formation of Shock waves.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] It is important to slow the flow (lower speed means less pressure losses or Pressure drop) when it travels through ducts connecting the different parts.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] How well the individual components contribute to turning fuel into thrust is quantified by measures like efficiencies for the compressors, turbines and combustor and pressure losses for the ducts.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] These are shown as lines on a Thermodynamic cycle diagram.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The engine efficiency, or thermal efficiency, known as $\eta _{th}$ . is dependent on the Thermodynamic cycle parameters, maximum pressure and temperature, and on component efficiencies, $\eta _{compressor}$ , $\eta _{combustion}$ and $\eta _{turbine}$ and duct pressure losses.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The engine needs compressed air for itself just to run successfully.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] This air comes from its own compressor and is called secondary air.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] It does not contribute to making thrust so makes the engine less efficient.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] It is used to preserve the mechanical integrity of the engine, to stop parts overheating and to prevent oil escaping from bearings for example.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Only some of this air taken from the compressors returns to the turbine flow to contribute to thrust production.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Any reduction in the amount needed improves the engine efficiency.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Again, it will be known for a particular engine design that a reduced requirement for cooling flow of x% will reduce the specific fuel consumption by y%.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] In other words, less fuel will be required to give take-off thrust, for example.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] All of the above considerations are basic to the engine running on its own and, at the same time, doing nothing useful, i.e. it is not moving an aircraft or supplying energy for the aircraft's electrical, hydraulic and air systems.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] In the aircraft the engine gives away some of its thrust-producing potential, or fuel, to power these systems.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] These requirements, which cause installation losses, reduce its efficiency.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] It is using some fuel that does not contribute to the engine's thrust.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Finally, when the aircraft is flying the propelling jet itself contains wasted kinetic energy after it has left the engine.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] This is quantified by the term propulsive, or Froude, efficiency $\eta _{p}$ and may be reduced by redesigning the engine to give it bypass flow and a lower speed for the propelling jet, for example as a turboprop or turbofan engine.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] At the same time forward speed increases the $\eta _{th}$ by increasing the Overall pressure ratio.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The overall efficiency of the engine at flight speed is defined as $\eta _{o}=\eta _{p}\eta _{th}$ .
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The $\eta _{o}$ at flight speed depends on how well the intake compresses the air before it is handed over to the engine compressors.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The intake compression ratio, which can be as high as 32:1 at Mach 3, adds to that of the engine compressor to give the Overall pressure ratio and $\eta _{th}$ for the Thermodynamic cycle.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] How well it does this is defined by its pressure recovery or measure of the losses in the intake.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Mach 3 manned flight has provided an interesting illustration of how these losses can increase dramatically in an instant.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The North American XB-70 Valkyrie and Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird at Mach 3 each had pressure recoveries of about 0.8, due to relatively low losses during the compression process, i.e. through systems of multiple shocks.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] During an 'unstart' the efficient shock system would be replaced by a very inefficient single shock beyond the inlet and an intake pressure recovery of about 0.3 and a correspondingly low pressure ratio.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The propelling nozzle at speeds above about Mach 2 usually has extra internal thrust losses because the exit area is not big enough as a trade-off with external afterbody drag.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Although a bypass engine improves propulsive efficiency it incurs losses of its own inside the engine itself.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Machinery has to be added to transfer energy from the gas generator to a bypass airflow.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The low loss from the propelling nozzle of a turbojet is added to with extra losses due to inefficiencies in the added turbine and fan.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] These may be included in a transmission, or transfer, efficiency $\eta _{T}$ .
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] However, these losses are more than made up by the improvement in propulsive efficiency.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] There are also extra pressure losses in the bypass duct and an extra propelling nozzle.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] With the advent of turbofans with their loss-making machinery what goes on inside the engine has been separated by Bennett, for example, between gas generator and transfer machinery giving $\eta _{o}=\eta _{p}\eta _{th}\eta _{T}$ .
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] for all jet engines the *propulsive efficiency* is highest as the exhaust jet velocity gets closer to the vehicle speed as this gives the smallest residual kinetic energy.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] For an airbreathing engine an exhaust velocity equal to the vehicle velocity, or a $\eta _{p}$ equal to one, gives zero thrust with no net momentum change.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] In addition to propulsive efficiency, another factor is *cycle efficiency*; a jet engine is a form of heat engine.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Heat engine efficiency is determined by the ratio of temperatures reached in the engine to that exhausted at the nozzle.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] This has improved constantly over time as new materials have been introduced to allow higher maximum cycle temperatures.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] For example, composite materials, combining metals with ceramics, have been developed for HP turbine blades, which run at the maximum cycle temperature.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The efficiency is also limited by the overall pressure ratio that can be achieved.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Cycle efficiency is highest in rocket engines (~60+%), as they can achieve extremely high combustion temperatures.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Cycle efficiency in turbojet and similar is nearer to 30%, due to much lower peak cycle temperatures.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The combustion efficiency of most aircraft gas turbine engines at sea level takeoff conditions is almost 100%.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] It decreases nonlinearly to 98% at altitude cruise conditions.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Air-fuel ratio ranges from 50:1 to 130:1.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] For any type of combustion chamber there is a *rich* and *weak limit* to the air-fuel ratio, beyond which the flame is extinguished.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The range of air-fuel ratio between the rich and weak limits is reduced with an increase of air velocity.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] If the increasing air mass flow reduces the fuel ratio below certain value, flame extinction occurs.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] A closely related (but different) concept to energy efficiency is the rate of consumption of propellant mass.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Propellant consumption in jet engines is measured by **specific fuel consumption**, **specific impulse**, or **effective exhaust velocity**.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Specific impulse and effective exhaust velocity are strictly proportional, whereas specific fuel consumption is inversely proportional to the others.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] For air-breathing engines such as turbojets, energy efficiency and propellant (fuel) efficiency are much the same thing, since the propellant is a fuel and the source of energy.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] In rocketry, the propellant is also the exhaust, and this means that a high energy propellant gives better propellant efficiency but can in some cases actually give *lower* energy efficiency.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] It can be seen in the table (just below) that the subsonic turbofans such as General Electric's CF6 turbofan use a lot less fuel to generate thrust for a second than did the Concorde's Rolls-Royce/Snecma Olympus 593 turbojet.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] However, since energy is force times distance and the distance per second was greater for the Concorde, the actual power generated by the engine for the same amount of fuel was higher for the Concorde at Mach 2 than the CF6.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Thus, the Concorde's engines were more efficient in terms of energy per distance traveled.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The thrust-to-weight ratio of jet engines with similar configurations varies with scale, but is mostly a function of engine construction technology.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] For a given engine, the lighter the engine, the better the thrust-to-weight is, the less fuel is used to compensate for drag due to the lift needed to carry the engine weight, or to accelerate the mass of the engine.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] As can be seen in the following table, rocket engines generally achieve much higher thrust-to-weight ratios than duct engines such as turbojet and turbofan engines.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] This is primarily because rockets almost universally use dense liquid or solid reaction mass which gives a much smaller volume and hence the pressurization system that supplies the nozzle is much smaller and lighter for the same performance.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Duct engines have to deal with air which is two to three orders of magnitude less dense and this gives pressures over much larger areas, which in turn results in more engineering materials being needed to hold the engine together and for the air compressor.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Propeller engines handle larger air mass flows, and give them smaller acceleration, than jet engines.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Since the increase in air speed is small, at high flight speeds the thrust available to propeller-driven aeroplanes is small.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] However, at low speeds, these engines benefit from relatively high propulsive efficiency.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] On the other hand, turbojets accelerate a much smaller mass flow of intake air and burned fuel, but they then reject it at very high speed.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] When a de Laval nozzle is used to accelerate a hot engine exhaust, the outlet velocity may be locally supersonic.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Turbojets are particularly suitable for aircraft travelling at very high speeds.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Turbofans have a mixed exhaust consisting of the bypass air and the hot combustion product gas from the core engine.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The amount of air that bypasses the core engine compared to the amount flowing into the engine determines what is called a turbofan's bypass ratio (BPR).
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] While a turbojet engine uses all of the engine's output to produce thrust in the form of a hot high-velocity exhaust gas jet, a turbofan's cool low-velocity bypass air yields between 30% and 70% of the total thrust produced by a turbofan system.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Rocket engines have extremely high exhaust velocity and thus are best suited for high speeds (hypersonic) and great altitudes.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Rocket engines are more efficient than even scramjets above roughly Mach 15.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] With the exception of scramjets, jet engines, deprived of their inlet systems can only accept air at around half the speed of sound.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The inlet system's job for transonic and supersonic aircraft is to slow the air and perform some of the compression.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The limit on maximum altitude for engines is set by flammability – at very high altitudes the air becomes too thin to burn, or after compression, too hot.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] For turbojet engines altitudes of about 40 km appear to be possible, whereas for ramjet engines 55 km may be achievable.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Scramjets may theoretically manage 75 km.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Rocket engines of course have no upper limit.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] At more modest altitudes, flying faster compresses the air at the front of the engine, and this greatly heats the air.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The upper limit is usually thought to be about Mach 5–8, as above about Mach 5.5, the atmospheric nitrogen tends to react due to the high temperatures at the inlet and this consumes significant energy.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The exception to this is scramjets which may be able to achieve about Mach 15 or more, as they avoid slowing the air, and rockets again have no particular speed limit.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The noise emitted by a jet engine has many sources.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] These include, in the case of gas turbine engines, the fan, compressor, combustor, turbine and propelling jet/s.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The propelling jet produces jet noise which is caused by the violent mixing action of the high speed jet with the surrounding air.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] In the subsonic case the noise is produced by eddies and in the supersonic case by Mach waves.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The sound power radiated from a jet varies with the jet velocity raised to the eighth power for velocities up to 600 m/s (2,000 ft/s) and varies with the velocity cubed above 600 m/s (2,000 ft/s).
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Thus, the lower speed exhaust jets emitted from engines such as high bypass turbofans are the quietest, whereas the fastest jets, such as rockets, turbojets, and ramjets, are the loudest.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] For commercial jet aircraft the jet noise has reduced from the turbojet through bypass engines to turbofans as a result of a progressive reduction in propelling jet velocities.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] For example, the JT8D, a bypass engine, has a jet velocity of 400 m/s (1,450 ft/s) whereas the JT9D, a turbofan, has jet velocities of 300 m/s (885 ft/s) (cold) and 400 m/s (1,190 ft/s)(hot).
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The advent of the turbofan replaced the very distinctive jet noise with another sound known as "buzz saw" noise.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The origin is the shockwaves originating at the supersonic fan blade tip at takeoff thrust.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Adequate heat transfer away from the working parts of the jet engine is critical to maintaining strength of engine materials and ensuring long life for the engine.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] After 2016, research is ongoing in the development of transpiration cooling techniques to jet engine components.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] In a jet engine, each major rotating section usually has a separate gauge devoted to monitoring its speed of rotation.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Depending on the make and model, a jet engine may have an N1 gauge that monitors the low-pressure compressor section and/or fan speed in turbofan engines.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] The gas generator section may be monitored by an N2 gauge, while triple spool engines may have an N3 gauge as well.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Each engine section rotates at many thousands RPM.
[src:jet-engine/jet-engine-p02] Their gauges therefore are calibrated in percent of a nominal speed rather than actual RPM, for ease of display and interpretation.
